DOCUMENT();

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
#           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
#           "PGgraphmacros.pl",
#           "extraAnswerEvaluators.pl",
#           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
#           "parserPopUp.pl",
"MathObjects.pl",
"AnswerFormatHelp.pl",
"PGcourse.pl",
           );

TEXT(beginproblem());

Context("Numeric");


$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$p = random(1,3,1);
$q = random($p+2,6,1);
$y = random(7,15,2);
$bot = $p*$q;
$a_disp = "$y/$bot";
$a_math = "\frac{$y}{$bot}";
$ans = "($a_disp)*(x-$p)*(x-$q)";

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
Find a formula for the quadratic function whose graph has \(y\)-intercept at \( y = $y \) and zeros at \( x = $p \) and \( x = $q \).
$PAR
\( f(x) = \) \{ ans_rule(30) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("formulas") \}
END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

ANS(Compute("$ans")->cmp() );

#ANS(fun_cmp( $ans,vars=>'x') );

Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR
The function has zeros at \( x= $p \) and \( x= $q \), so it could be of the form \( \ y=a(x - $p)(x-$q) \) .  Since \( y= $y \) when \( x= 0 \), we know that \( y=a(0-$p)(0-$q)= $bot a=$y \), so \( a= $a_math \).  Therefore,
\[ f(x) =  $a_math (x - $p)(x-$q ). \]

END_SOLUTION
Context()->normalStrings;

COMMENT('MathObject version');
ENDDOCUMENT();
